<title>The !khau lizard and the rainclouds – springbok hunting follows rain; and the song of the !khau lizard</title>
<summary><i>The !khaü (a lizard of the genus Agama), which interferes with the coming of the rain–clouds. Springbok hunting follows the rain. (L VIII.-3. 6232 rev.-6234 rev., 6259-6266, 6269-6271).</i> The<i> !khau, </i>or Agama lizard (or <i>kochelman</i>) lies in the Driedoorn tree and frustrates the rain&apos;s clouds so the rain does not fall. The people make the <i>!khau</i> come down from the Driedoorn tree so that the rain-clouds will bring the rain, which in turn brings the springbok. </summary><comments>1) p.6259v: The song of the !khau (or Agama Lizard), 2) See also <i>The death of the !kau (a lizard of the genus Agama) </i>and<i> The !kau who brought home his own flesh as food, </i>3) This story is found in Book VIII-3</comments><date>13 – 19 February 1878</date><storypages>6232v-6234v, 6259-6266, 6269-6271</storypages><category>The Rain and Rain&apos;s water</category><author>|han≠kass'o (Klein Jantje) (VIII)</author><keyword><kw>rain</kw><subkw>the !khau lizard and the rain–clouds</subkw></keyword>
